                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-date&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;comment-link&quot; href=&quot;#comment3842467_3653500&quot;&gt;&lt;span title=&quot;2010-09-06 18:28:40Z, License: CC BY-SA 2.5&quot; class=&quot;relativetime-clean&quot;&gt;Sep 6, 2010 at 18:28&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;Paul, I agree. But as I said I used if for a specific purpose, and that is for a data entry operation where you have many kinds of forms. I am revising the design now that I have learnt NHibernate but back then I needed the flexibity to design the form in ASP.NET and use the textbox ids as key in the key/value pair.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;/users/125214/raj&quot; title=&quot;1,726 reputation&quot; class=&quot;comment-user&quot;&gt;Raj&lt;/a&gt;
